The length of the explanatory notes calls I fancy for less ex- cuse. This very year three centuries have elapsed since Lambinus published the first edition of his Lucretius3 and from that day to this nothing new and systematical, nothing that displays pains and research has been done for the elucidation of our author. Transcendant as are the merits of that illustrious scholar, what was suited to 1564 can hardly satisfy the wants of 1864. No defence then is needed for the extent of this division of my commentary: if it were done over again, more would probably have to be added than taken away. It will not be so easy perhaps to excuse the translation. This however is really a part of the explanatory notes3 and if it had been left undone, they must have been enlarged in many directions. Our author too unless I am mistaken will admit of being thus treated better than most; and the fashion of literal translations seems to be gaining ground in this country as well as in Germany and France.
